-- CSN, Camargo Correa, Banorte, Aeroportuario: Latin America Equity Preview
-- Andres Martinez
-- 2010-07-15T03:00:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-15/cia-siderurgica-banorte-aeroportuario-latin-america-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  fell 0.7 percent to 3,870.99.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock.  
 Brazil  
 Camargo Correa Desenvolvimento Imobiliario SA  (CCIM3 BS):
The Brazilian real estate company reported second quarter
contracted sales rose 82 percent to 314.8 million reais. Camargo
Correa fell 0.6 percent to 5.37 reais.  
 Cia. Siderurgica Nacional SA  (CSNA3 BS): Brazil’s third
biggest steelmaker sold $1 billion of 10 year bonds to yield
6.625 percent. CSN, as the company is also known, fell 1.5
percent to 26.95 reais.  
 MRV Engenharia e Participacoes SA  (MRVE3 BS): The Brazilian
real estate company reported that second-quarter contracted
sales rose 15 percent to 981.9 million reais. New projects
increased 81 percent to 1.1 billion reais. MRV rose 3.2 percent
to 14.50 reais.  
 Mexico  
 Controladora Comercial Mexicana SAB  (COMERUBC MM): The
Mexican supermarket chain that defaulted on debt in 2008, said
it filed for pre-approved bankruptcy. The company said that 98
percent of its creditors support the filing and all of its debt
will be restructured under the agreement reached with them.
Comerci, as the company is also known, rose 0.1 percent to 11.75
pesos.  
 Grupo Aeroportuario del Sureste SAB  (ASURB MM): The
operator of Mexico’s Cancun airport may rise after the country’s
Tourism Minister  Gloria Guevara  said foreign tourist visits will
return to 2008 levels this year. Asur, as the company is known,
rose 1.6 percent to 64.43 pesos.  
 Grupo Financiero Banorte SAB  (GFNORTEO MM): Mexico’s
second-largest publicly traded bank sold $300 million of 5-year
bonds to yield 262.5 basis points above U.S. Treasuries. Banorte
rose 0.8 percent to 50 pesos.  
